Girls, series two finale, Sky Atlantic, review
Alice Vincent reviews the final episode in the second series of Lena Dunham's Girls. 2.5
Lena Dunham stars as Hannah Horvath in HBO's Girls By Alice Vincent, Entertainment writer, online
8:20AM GMT 19 Mar 2013
Follow Comments
The problem with the second series of Girls (Sky Atlantic) was that it had stopped being about the girls. Lena Dunham - the creator, director and star of the cult HBO show that has caused many to dub her the voice of a generation - experimented more over these 10 episodes.
We’ve seen the central character, Hannah (played by Dunham), star alone in one episode, which marked the start of the, perhaps inevitable but rapid, descent of her mental state. Meanwhile, Marnie (Allison Williams) is working as a hostess and embarrassing herself at parties, despite still being encased in Stepford Wife trainer-tailoring. Shoshanna (Zosia Mamet) has gained an independence from the boyfriend she desperately craved, and Jessa (Jemima Kirke) has just gone AWOL. We haven’t seen the girls together, all in one room, during the entire series.
So despite the season finale being called Together, it was unlikely the title characters would reunite.
Instead, rather awkwardly, they reunited with their past lovers - or found new ones. To swooping orchestral strings, mad dashes through subway stations and grand, tearful talks about the future. Girls may have started out as an antidote to the sitcom, but the finale was more romcom territory - and after the previous bleak episodes touching on subjects such as OCD, rape and abandonment, it sat awkwardly.
However, even this couldn’t dampen Dunham’s writing. Marnie telling on-off boyfriend Charlie (Christopher Abbott) she wanted to “sit and watch [him] die” was a perfectly sharp barb in a saccharine scene. Hannah talked, with painful reminiscence, about being sheltered from the shards of broken glass to friendly ex-junkie neighbour Laird, who was neatly re-introduced after only featuring in episode three.
Related Articles
Girls, series 3, episodes 1 and 2, review
20 Jan 2014
The caustic brilliance of Girls
23 Oct 2012
Sex and the gritty world of kidulthood
02 Oct 2012
Girls: series two, Sky Atlantic
15 Jan 2013
But some of the best lines went to the boys, who seemed to be doing rather better at "almost kind of getting it together". Dunham’s male characters have been the most engaging in this series, and they didn’t disappoint in the finale.
Shoshanna's boyfriend Ray discussed girl problems with his boss Hermie, which included a frank and funny dissection of Shoshanna’s croissant-shaped handbag, before he landed a promotion in "classy" Brooklyn Heights. Hannah's ex, Adam, appeared to be entering into a normal, adult relationship with another woman, smashing the boat he’d been constructing during his break-up from Hannah - an ironic symbol of freedom, if one a little hackneyed.
As for Charlie, well, now he’d landed his sweetheart Marnie to match his good fortune.
It was all a little cosy, really. Laird said to Hannah: “I think it’s a pretty dark scene inside your head.” Perhaps so, but the world Dunham has created here is far more rosy than it purports to be. Follow Telegraph TV & Radio on Twitter
