ThinCats' business bonds a 'precursor' to full market
Peer-to-peer lender's bond scheme, which links retail investors with entrepreneurs, is a "stepping stone" to a full small business bond market, the company's managing director claims. From a borrowing small company’s perspective, the debt will be similar to a conventional bank loan with monthly repayments. By James Hurley
5:43PM GMT 05 Mar 2011
Follow Comments
When Business Club, think tank Nesta and Conservative MP Sam Gyimah proposed a bond market for small companies last year, critics pointed out a number of hurdles.
Among them were the possibility of punitive fees, the difficulty in rating risk in small businesses and uncertainty over their demand for long term debt. The Government is still consulting on how these challenges can be overcome to stimulate such a market, but it may have been beaten to the punch by a “peer-to-peer” lending start-up.
ThinCats, a website that links business borrowers with retail savers, has launched a bond scheme in partnership with fund manager Innvotec that it believes will encourage retail investors to back entrepreneurs. Savers invest a minimum of £5,000 for a gross return of 8pc over three years, with funds invested in an “actively managed” portfolio of secured small company loans vetted by Innvotec, which is authorised by the Financial Services Authority. The company said no loan will represent more than 7.5pc of the funds committed to the bond issue, which is aiming to raise £1m. Related Articles
LSE: Government agency needed to boost bonds for SMEs
13 Mar 2012
Learn from Germany on lending, FSB urges
28 Feb 2012
UK Treasury in 'credit easing' bond talks with LSE
29 Oct 2011
Advisers' pessimism hits entrepreneurs
05 Mar 2011
From a borrowing small company’s perspective, the debt will be similar to a conventional bank loan with monthly repayments. Kevin Caley, ThinCats managing director, said the bond would move peer-to-peer lending “into the mainstream, making it worthy of consideration by any investor or their adviser”. Peer-to-peer lending markets, which are unregulated, traditionally require savers to pick small companies to back or use automatic systems to spread investments across a number of companies. However, the scheme doesn’t resolve another issue for small business bonds – the lack of a secondary market. The bond will not be listed, although Mr Caley said he sees it as a “stepping stone to a full bond market for these loans so people can buy and sell them as they wish”. Fees for the borrower include a £950 for listing and legal documents, a 1.5pc premium on the interest rate determined by the auction on the ThinCats site and a “success fee” of between 2pc and 6pc. Beyond the Banks
