Buttermilk chicken with winter slaw recipe
Tender chicken pieces marinated in buttermilk and garlic, with a crisp raw-vegetable slaw. Buttermilk chicken with winter slaw Photo: LAURA EDWARDS	<
>
Article
Food trends to watch out for in 2013
Article
Conchas borrachas recipe
By Diana Henry
3:00PM GMT 10 Jan 2013
Follow Comments
Serves six
Buttermilk does amazing things to chicken, tenderising and flavouring it through to the bone. If you can’t find kohlrabi you could either just leave it out or substitute 200g (7oz) mooli or ordinary radishes. For the chicken:
560ml (19fl oz) buttermilk 6 cloves garlic, crushed
1 tsp ground cayenne
12 chicken joints (thighs, drumsticks or breasts on the bone) For the slaw:
½ savoy cabbage
½ small red cabbage
1 large fennel bulb
juice of ½ lemon 1 small kohlrabi bulb 1 tart green apple
1½ tsp Dijon mustard
20ml (¾fl oz) cider vinegar
2 tbsp caster sugar
50ml (2fl oz) olive oil
50ml (2fl oz) groundnut oil
½ red onion, very finely sliced into thin crescent-moon shapes
35g (1¼oz) chopped pecans Mix together the buttermilk, garlic and cayenne with plenty of salt and pepper. Put the chicken into a container and pour over the marinade. Turn the pieces over, cover and refrigerate for 24 hours, turning the chicken every so often. Related Articles
Pickled carrots with chilli and coriander recipe
10 Jan 2013
Gently shake off the excess marinade (but don’t wipe the chicken clean). Put the joints into a roasting-tin. Roast in an oven preheated to 190°C/375°F/gas mark 5 for 40 minutes, or until cooked through. Cover with foil if the surface is getting too dark. Meanwhile, make the slaw. Remove and discard the core from both cabbages and shred them finely. Quarter the fennel, trim the tops and remove coarse outer leaves. Core each quarter. Cut into wafer-thin slices using a very sharp knife or mandolin. Put into a bowl and toss in the lemon juice. Slice the kohlrabi wafer-thin and add to the bowl. Halve and core the apple, cut it into matchsticks and toss with the fennel mixture. Put the mustard into a small jug and whisk in the cider vinegar and sugar, then oils. Season. (For a more muted dressing add 1 tbsp of whipping cream.) Put all the vegetables, the apple, onion and nuts into a serving-bowl. Toss with the dressing. Season to taste. Serve the chicken joints on a warm platter with the slaw on the side. Recommended wine: Les Grands Cailloux Viognier IGP Pays d'Oc 2010. Get it from Telegraph Wine > The peach and apricot notes with the weight of the wine will be in harmony with the apple and buttermilk chicken.
