Police appeal over Surrey stabbing
Abigail Witchalls with her son Joseph 11:49AM BST 22 Apr 2005
A man and woman have been arrested in connection with the stabbing of Abigail Witchalls after turning themselves in, police have said. The 28-year-old man and 29-year-old woman went voluntarily to Leatherhead police station. Mrs Witchalls, a 26-year-old mother of one, is still in a critical condition but is said by police to have "slightly improved" today as her family hold a vigil by her hospital bed. She suffered a single three inch stab wound to the back of her neck as she took her 21-month-old son out for a walk in the quiet Surrey village of Little Bookham on Wednesday.
The attack is believed to have been unprovoked. Det Supt Adrian Harper, leading the investigation, warned: "This person may strike again."
He said the details of the attack are still very sketchy as the only people who witnessed the crime were the victim and her son Joseph. When police arrived, Mrs Witchalls was on the ground and her son was out of his buggy beside her. The child did not appear to have been harmed, Mr Harper said. Police confirmed today that Mrs Witchalls had been able to whisper some words to the neighbours who went to her aid. But detectives were not prepared to release details of exactly what she said. Mr Harper said there were no signs of a struggle on the narrow muddy path where the attack took place. He also confirmed that although she had been carrying a rucksack containing cards and cash, nothing was taken. News
