The One Where Dave Spends Even More Time with His Family
Even on the beach in Cornwall, Dave remains on top of things, in the latest instalment of our political sitcom.
'Tough morning, darling?': David and Samantha Cameron on the beach in Cornwall Photo: GETTY	By Iain Hollingshead
7:00PM BST 27 Aug 2011
Comments
“What's that, Daddy?” asked Arthur. “It’s a scale model of the Libyan capital, Tripoli,” said Dave. “Daddy is a very important man and has to stay in touch with world events at all times.”
“By building a sandcastle?” asked five-year-old Arthur scornfully. Dave yawned and decided to ignore him. Time for a mid-morning siesta. Putting down his bucket and spade, he lay back contentedly on the Cornish beach, the sand between his toes, the soothing sound of the waves lapping on the shore. Golly, he loved being Prime Minister: free car, excellent pension and as much annual leave as he liked. “Tough morning?” His reverie was broken by Sam, back from the shops with a picnic of Duchy Originals. Related Articles
Nick Clegg focuses on wealth as he eases out of bed with the Tories
29 Aug 2011
Libya: a new sense of freedom on Algeria Square
27 Aug 2011
David Cameron: no more children for Samantha and me
25 Aug 2011
David Cameron cuts Cornish holiday short as rebels enter Tripoli
22 Aug 2011
Libya: Nick Clegg defends David Cameron for going on holiday
23 Aug 2011
“Exhausting,” said Dave, sitting up and rubbing his eyes. “Honestly, much more of this and I’ll need a holiday to recover from all the holidays.”
“Just make sure that whenever you resign, you don’t tell the press that you want to spend more time with your family,” said Sam. “They’ll never believe you.”
Dave’s laughter was cut short by the sound of his mobile. He looked at the number on the screen and wondered whether to leave it to go to the voicemail he’d recorded back in April, just before their first summer holiday: “Please leave a message and I’ll get back to you after the party conference season.”
This time, however, he decided to pick up. “Hello, Nick,” he said. “I’m glad you called. Could you see if Jacqui’s got any spare prisoners she could send round to North Kensington to give our drawing room a fresh lick of paint while we’re gone?”
Nick, however, did not sound in the mood for jokes. “I’m sorry to tell you that there has been a rather worrying development in international affairs,” he said. “Oh, I’ve read about that,” said Dave breezily. “I didn’t think Anne Hathaway’s accent was that bad.”
“No, no,” cried Nick. “It’s Libya. Gaddafi appears to be on the way out.”
“Oh him,” yawned Dave. “I know all about that, of course. Quite a coup, wouldn’t you say?”
“But what should we do next?” asked Nick. “Oh, I don’t know,” said Dave, rubbing out the Libyan leader’s compound with his big toe. “Let’s leave it be. It worked out fine in Iraq, didn’t it? Anyway, can’t you just ring Barack? He’ll tell you what to do.”
“He’s on a cycling holiday with his family,” said Nick, sniffing a little. “It’s not easy being the international fort-holder, you know.”
Dave tried and failed to stifle a giggle. “I think you should know,” Nick continued sternly, “that people are beginning to murmur about your absence. Where’s Dave, they cry. Has he lost his grip on a country in flames? Has he let the rebels take over the streets? Which luxurious bunker is he holed up in now? Is he, like Gaddafi, secretly stalking the streets of our capital?”
“Oh, do relax, Nick,” said Dave, gesturing to Sam to bring him another strawberry Daiquiri. “Why don’t you just go out and paint the town red? Or yourself blue...”
