Labour 'gives up' on mixed-sex hospital wards
Figures reveal that 31 pc of NHS trusts admit to having fully mixed wards - without any form of partition By Nic Fleming,
Medical Correspondent
8:10PM GMT 28 Jan 2008
Labour has admitted it had abandoned its historic commitment to eliminate mixed-sex wards from NHS hospitals.
Health minister Lord Darzi of Denham told the House of Lords that the key manifesto pledge repeated in 1997 and 2001 was "an aspiration that cannot be met".
Lord Darzi said the Government was committed to single sex accommodation, but that this could be achieved by splitting up mixed wards into bays.
Patient charities have campaigned for years for an end to male and female patients sharing facilities in NHS hospitals, and a number of women have been the victims of assaults from men in mixed-sex wards.
Related Articles
U-turn on pledge to scrap mixed-sex wards
22 Dec 2007
Pledge to abolish mixed-sex wards by year's end
15 Aug 2010
Catherine Murphy, of The Patients Association, said: "For more than 10 years we have had Tony Blair and successive ministers calling for an end to mixed sex wards.
"This is a U-turn. They have given up on the MRSA target and now they have given up on mixed sex wards.
"What patients, especially female patients, mean by single sex accommodation is being cared for on a ward where only patients of their sex are present, and not sharing bathroom and toilet facilities."
Norman Lamb, Liberal Democrat health spokesman, said: "This is an astonishing admission of failure on an issue of crucial importance to patients.
"The Government has flip-flopped on this manifesto commitment for over 10 years."
Last month The Daily Telegraph reported comments from a Department of Health official who said: "We have to get away from this idea of single-sex wards.
"We are moving away from a set target on single-sex accommodation. It is possible to envisage patient privacy and dignity with patients of different sexes on the same wards but with proper segregation."
Asked to clarify, the official said a mixed ward divided into bays by fixed partitions - not necessarily fixed to the ceiling, but high enough that patients perceive they are in a separate room - counted as single-sex accommodation.
At the time Health Secretary Alan Johnson denied the statements amounted to a U-turn or a retreat by the Government.
However yesterday Lord Darzi told fellow peers: "Our guidance requires the provision of single sex accommodation, not wards.
"This may mean single rooms or single sex bays within a mixed ward as well as single sex wards.
"The only way we are going to have single sex wards in the NHS is to build the whole of the NHS into single rooms.
"It is not achievable in transforming a ward into a single sex ward. That is an aspiration that cannot be met."
Tory Lord Naseby responded: "After 10 years of this Government the removal of mixed wards is no longer part of their policy, and the whole issue is now fudged totally by the answer that you have just given.
"I have just come back from Sri Lanka and visited the public wards there. They are 100 per cent single sex. If a developing country can do it why can't this country do it?"
Figures obtained by the Conservatives last month showed 31 per cent of healthcare trusts admitted still having fully mixed wards - without any form of partition and excluding intensive care, emergency and children's wards.
This is almost double the amount stated in a report released last May by the Chief Nursing Officer.
A quarter of trusts reported washing facilities were not segregated on all wards, while 29 per cent said separate lavatories were not always available.
In May, Patricia Hewitt, the then Health Secretary, said there was more to be done to "meet our commitment to eliminate mixed-sex wards". Two years ago Miss Hewitt stated that partitioned bays were "not good enough".
In November 1996 Tony Blair, then Leader of the Opposition, attacked John Major, saying: "Why has the Prime Minister not yet made good the promise given two years ago to eliminate mixed-sex wards in our hospitals?"
The 1997 Labour Party manifesto stated "we will work towards the elimination of mixed-sex wards", while the manifesto of 2001 stated "mixed sex wards will be abolished".
Kate Jopling, of Help the Aged, said: "Sharing mixed sex wards remains an ongoing concern for many older people who may find the experience distressing and an inappropriate infringement of their privacy, and therefore dignity."
A Department of Health spokesman said Monday night: "Lord Darzi's comments were fully in line with the Government's long-standing commitment on mixed-sex accommodation. The aim of the NHS is to reduce mixed-sex accommodation and ensure privacy and dignity for all patients.
"But sometimes the need to treat and admit will take priority over complete segregation. The NHS will not turn patients away because the 'right sex' bed is not immediately available."
