Angel Cabrera's dignity in defeat highlights the beauty of sport's slow-burners
They say you never remember the loser, but it will be a long time before I forget that little thumbs-up Angel Cabrera gave Adam Scott at the beginning of their Masters play-off, when the young Australian fired off a perfect drive.
Angel Cabrera's dignity in defeat highlights the beauty of sport's slow-burners Photo: AP	By Sarah Crompton
6:00AM BST 17 Apr 2013
Follow Comments
Nor am I likely to lose from memory the breadth of his smile when his young opponent won the Green Jacket by the narrowest of margins, or the warmth of his embrace. It went beyond mere sportsmanship to speak to the character of the man; it suggested exactly the kind of person who can walk around a golf course with his son as a caddie without ever coming to blows. It cannot have been easy for Cabrera to behave like that. If he had won, he would have been, at 43, the second oldest person to win the Masters, following Jack Nicklaus’s extraordinary 1986 triumph at the age of 46. He would have been the first grandfather. And for a man languishing at 269th in the world, it is the kind of opportunity that will not come along very often any more. But he has heart and he has class. And he knew that the difference between winning and losing on Sunday night was the width of a centimetre. I wonder if Tiger Woods could have behaved with such effortless generosity. Somehow, I doubt it; he can lose with dignity but rarely with good grace. So a good guy lost – but a good guy won, too. Cabrera summed it up: “Adam is truly a good winner. Obviously I would have been happier if I’d won, but he’s a great person and a great player.” Which is true and it was a sign of the kind of man Scott is that, in the very moment of his victory, he dedicated his triumph to Greg Norman. Norman, of course, is the other loser you can never forget, not least for the desperate agonies of squandering a six-shot lead at Augusta to Nick Faldo in 1996. He bore that bravely, but it was tough to watch, let alone to live through. Related Articles
Scott soothes Aussie angst at Masters
15 Apr 2013
Scott proves a choke can make, not break, a career
16 Apr 2013
Scott first Aussie to win Masters
15 Apr 2013
Norman: Scott can be best ever
15 Apr 2013
Caddie secures his 14th major
15 Apr 2013
Scott: I'll have a beer with Greg
15 Apr 2013
That is the thing about golf. Spectators and players are in it for the long haul, and amid the piercing pressure of a major championship, the stories that emerge are all about who the players really are, and what is going on in their minds. In this, it is much like Test cricket, which is the ultimate slow-burning thriller, a book whose pages fill the sunny days with twists and turns of drama and psychology. The Nightwatchman, a new quarterly collection of elegant and interesting writing about cricket, published by Wisden, and co-edited by my colleague Tanya Aldred, has an excellent essay by the novelist Patrick Neate on this very theme. He argues that all sport is narrative, but most “are plot driven pulp, built on archetypes of heroism and villainy”. Cricket, he argues, is driven not by plot but by character, “and the nuances to be found therein are, if not limitless, as diverse as humanity itself”. As we enter the season where brave men wear white, it is a fascinating way to look at the sport. It explains why – to the amazement of many – the England Test team’s series draw in New Zealand was greeted by most fans as the most stirring victory, and one in which, once again, good character could be revealed. As one of my friends wrote to me at the time: “What other sport is there when 22 players can bash one another about, and swear at each other for 15 days and when it’s all over, walk off the battlefield arm in arm with the opposition, patting one another on the back?”
This too, goes beyond sportsmanship into something deeper. Neate sums it up: “Cricket, like a novel, like life, often ends in moral stalemate. And it’s all the better for it.” Which is another way of saying that those sports which divulge character over a period of time are infinitely more fascinating than those which provide the adrenalin rush of excitement but do not leave you with the insight into human nature that a kindly thumbs-up or a gentle pat on the back can sometimes provide. To buy 'The Nightwatchman' visit thenightwatchman.net
