Perfect end to a perfect day
A good country walk is much more enjoyable if you book into the right hotel. Fiona Duncan finds great places to stay in spectacular surroundings.
Image 1 of 5	The Bell Hotel, Skenfrith Image 1 of 5	The Ashcome estate, now home to Madonna and Guy Ritchie Image 1 of 5	Museum Inn, Farnham Image 1 of 5	Cowley Manor Image 1 of 5	Holkham Hall 12:01AM BST 11 Oct 2005
Comments
I'm all for exercise, as long as I'm rewarded for it. There's got to be serious pleasure in my keep-fit regime and I can think of nothing more pleasurable than a weekend away, walking in beautiful landscape, returning at the end of the day to good food and a warm bed in a welcoming hotel. Over the past few months I have stayed in six hotels in prime British walking country. These were picked not just for their quality, but also because their location allows guests to set out on a circular walking route on the first day, return for a long soak, a good dinner and a comfortable night, then strike out in another direction next morning after an indulgent breakfast. Cresting a hill after an eight-mile tramp and seeing the perfect inn where you are expected for the night - that's a proper reward.
The walks, hotels and practical details are described below. Suggestions for less expensive alternatives are given where appropriate. Welsh borders
The walk Monmouthshire has a flavour all its own: very green (but with red soil); not exactly rolling, but full of abrupt little hills, often topped with woodland, with plain, hardworking farmhouses tucked into their folds; cared for, yet delightfully free of the suburban air that can spoil so much of southern England; sleepy, lost in time, with few outside visitors (we encountered just four other walkers on the entire route). The Three Castles Walk, designed and waymarked by Monmouthshire County Council, is a 19-mile route that links three atmospheric Norman castles (two free, one with a small entrance fee), through woods and meadows, with many a stile to cross (any dog that has to be carried over, such as our portly spaniel, should be banned). The scenery is consistently beautiful, at times small-scale, magnificent at others, and the castles - Skenfrith, White and Grosmont - make absorbing and atmospheric goals. Our picnic spot, just after crossing the high wood between Grosmont and Skenfrith, had one of the loveliest views we had ever seen in Britain. Most people should easily manage the whole 19 miles in two days, although we didn't. We chatted too much, the dog was too heavy, the scenery too beautiful and the hotel too seductive, so we only completed two of the three legs. The hotel
The Bell, Skenfrith (01600 750235; www.skenfrith.co.uk; doubles from £95 per night, including breakfast), goes with this walk like wine with cheese. Right on the route, it's the perfect hotel for city-dwellers seeking their rural inner-selves. Situated on the River Monnow, it has a candlelit, flagstoned dining-room serving locally sourced modern British dishes; a well-organised wine list; a huge inglenook surrounded by sofas; and eight simple-sophisticated bedrooms. In the morning, the enormous Welsh breakfast will set you up for another day's delightful walking. The details
The walk is thoughtfully waymarked, but while it's fun trying to spot the next yellow marker, it's probably best to buy the Three Castles Walk booklet, available from Monmouth Tourist Information Centre (01600 713899; £3.95). If you start at the Bell and split the walk between two days, the hotel will pick you up at the end of the first; it will provide packed lunches and has a drying room, plus an unlimited supply of sticking plasters.
If you don't want to do such a long walk, the hotel has put together six others, equally lovely, and designed to complement the season. Dorset
The walk Once a hunting ground frequented by royalty, Cranborne Chase has the feel of an ancient place, with its ox droves, Roman roads and prehistoric earthworks, and its combination of woodland, rolling fields and steep scarps. With wide views, big skies and a few scattered villages, it makes for superb walking. Leaving the car by the pond at Tollard Royal, we blew away the cobwebs on Win Green, the highest point, with marvellous views, walking back alongside Madonna and Guy Ritchie's house, Ashcombe, which lies in its own valley (5.5 miles in all). The following morning we made an 8.5-mile exploration of the quiet Tarrant valley and the feudal village of Chettle, set in a wooded hollow, overlooked by its fine 18th-century manor house. We set off early as we wanted to be back at the Museum Inn for Sunday lunch - a good decision. The hotel
Cranborne Chase is closely associated with General Augustus Pitt-Rivers, the 19th-century archaeologist who built the Museum Inn, Farnham (01725 516261; www.museuminn.co.uk; doubles from £95 per night, including breakfast) to accommodate visitors to his nearby museum. Today it's owned by Vicky Elliot and Mark Stephenson, with cheery Australian staff and convivial, well-heeled customers (Madonna drops in from time to time). You can eat either in a cosy corner of the rambling bar, or in the elegant Shed restaurant, which is done out in crisp white and green. Mark Treasure's sophisticated bistro food ranges from pressed ham knuckle and guinea-fowl terrine to whole lobster and French fries, plus a great Sunday roast. The prettiest bedrooms are those in the inn itself, as opposed to the stables, and the best is the General's Bedroom, which has plenty of light and a four-poster. The details
The Win Green walk was devised by the hotel's owners, who will give you the directions and a marked-up Explorer Map 118 Shaftesbury&Cranborne Chase. The Tarrant Valley walk is from Adventurous Pub Walks in Dorset by Anne-Marie Edwards (Countryside Books, £7.99), also available from the Museum Inn, as are packed lunches. Cotswolds
The walk An exhilarating, strenuous, figure-of-eight ramble taking in Cotswold quarries and country churches. There are plenty of swoops and troughs as you climb high on to sheep pasture and dip down into quiet valleys. The northern (nine-mile) loop incorporates a particularly attractive section of the Cotswold Way, with spectacular wold and scarp views, including the striking rock pinnacle, Devil's Chimney.
The southern (six-mile) loop makes a tour of three charming villages, each with an interesting church. A main road interrupts more than once, but you soon walk away from it into a pleasing rural landscape. The hotel
The sort of exercise taken by the average guest at Cowley Manor, Cowley (01242 870900; www.cowleymanor.com; doubles from £230, including breakfast) ranges from carrying a laptop on to the terrace to working-out in the gym or swimming in one of the two pools at C-Side, the hotel's fine spa. Walking - that time-consuming, old fashioned pursuit - doesn't feature much (despite the row of complimentary wellies by the front door). The hotel's beautiful lake-filled Grade II-listed grounds and its position in prime Cotswold walking country remain something of a well-kept secret. It's not for granny (staff wear T-shirts and brothel creepers), but its seamless blend of stone grandeur and contemporary bliss-out suits stressed urbanites and their children. The elegant stone terrace is a suntrap, with views that promise rewarding walking.
Sit there and pull on your boots - you'll amaze your fellow guests - and when you return, you'll see why Cowley (which means cow pasture), with its plentiful water and its sheltering woods and hills, was a self-sufficient farming community from earliest times. Alternative accommodation
The Green Dragon Inn, Cockleford (01242 870271; www.buccaneer.co.uk/greendragon; doubles from £80 per night, including breakfast). The details The directions for the walk, which follow waymarked stony tracks and field paths, plus some Tarmac lanes, are available from the hotel, accompanied by a marked-up Explorer Map 179 Gloucester, Cheltenham & Stroud. If you want to take a packed lunch, you can choose from the hotel's delicious picnic menu. Norfolk
The Walk
Even if you stay in Holkham for several days, you need never stray from land belonging to the Earl of Leicester. As well as visiting stately Holkham Hall, you can follow a number of gentle walks around the estate, encompassing pinewoods, parkland, meadows, farmland and beaches. Starting from the hotel, we chose the Lake Walk, just over 3.5 miles, contrasting it next morning with the Beach Walk, which can be extended from two to 10 miles, as you wish. The former began in leafy, sun-dappled woodland, peppered with deer, passed St Withburga's church on its grassy knoll, then opened on to classic 18th-century landscaped parkland, complete with winding lake (trips by electric boat) and the hall's charming 17th-century thatched ice house. The latter is an enchanting and instructive meander (owned by the Earl of Leicester but managed as a reserve by English Nature) past lagoons and grazing marshes, through woods of Corsican pine and along the natural, dune-swept beach to the Lifeboat Station, beach huts and sailing boats at Wells-next-the-Sea. The hotel The theme may be colonial India, with colourful furnishings imported from Rajasthan, but The Victoria, Holkham (01328 711008; www.victoriaatholkham.co.uk; doubles from £120 per night, including breakfast), which was built in 1838 and given a major revamp in 2001 by Viscount Coke and his wife, feels thoroughly English in a laid-back, slightly scuffed, child-oriented sort of way. Though it's described as hip and stylish, it's more friendly and feel-good than that, with guests ranging from retired couples to familiar-faced actors. The food is a highlight (perfect fish and chips, and rib-eye steak were favourites), and there's an appealing buzz in the restaurant. The details Serious walkers can tramp nearby Peddars Way and Norfolk Coast Path National Trail, while circular walks in the Holkham area are described in Coastal Circular Walks in Norfolk by Joy and Charles Boldero, which is sold in local shops, including Holkham Art, Crafts and Fine Food Centre. Here you'll also find the Marshes Larder, an upmarket deli and café, where you can choose your picnic (or let the hotel do it for you) and have it packed in your rucksack or a pretty wicker basket. Directions for the Holkham Estate walks, including hand-painted maps, are available from the hotel and on the website. The park is occasionally closed to walkers - inquire first. Dogs must be kept on the lead. A perfect day (continued) >>>
